All of the stories that you hold to yourself about yourself are being told through the way you move.
•
Is it time to retell your story? 
_
Here’s some fun facts about me:

1. I LOVE being in big bodies of water. I’m slightly addicted to the feeling of floating. Perhaps it has to do with my Pisces Rising Sign. My mother says I was always a water baby.

2. My parents were in the Air Force. My mother resigned when I was born because they wanted her to go to Alaska and she wasn’t having that. 🙅🏾‍♀️

3. My father is from Saint Vincent and the Grenadines. He came to America as an immigrant in his early teens. He always encouraged my brother and I stay active. And I’m so grateful for his guidance. 🇻🇨

4. I have been practicing yoga for almost 9 years and teaching yoga for 7+ years. Ima be practicing for the rest of my life. 🧘🏾‍♀️

5. I’ve travelled to 13 countries. Hella passports, hella stamps. ✈️

To my fellow yoga teachers…

1. Remember to be intentional about your message. Drop nuggets of wisdom relatable to the current times. Be transparent with your students. Storytelling is always appreciated. Encourage dialogue.

2. Accessibility is important. No one wants to watch you perform a bunch difficult poses. Read the room. Walk around while you teach. Give multiple variations.

3. With every breath you take, life force is circulating through your vessel. You must be attentive to your own breath and your students’ breathing. Choose breathing techniques that relate to the theme of the class. Like, breath of fire wouldn’t be the best idea for a restorative class.

4. Your students deserve to be taken on a journey through the mind. Many folks are suffering from anxiety, depression and trauma that surfaces at wild times. Guided meditation is a moment for the teacher to assist with releasing the mental stress. Skipping this opportunity is not the best idea. Make an effort to talk at a neutral speed, without too many words.
_
#YogaTeachers have a special duty to hold space for folks to explore the depths of their mind, body and soul. It is not to be taken lightly. Preserve the authenticity of the practice. It’s okay to be creative with your classes but when you remove fundamental aspects of the practice… you may as well call it something else.

Imagine having parents who never taught you basic survival skills like swimming.

Imagine not having access to pools, springs or beaches.
_
Imagine being a child, knowing how to swim and not being allowed to swim freely because your parents didn’t want to do your hair.
_

_
Imagine having flashbacks of your ancestors being captured and transported over deep waters.
_
Being able to swim, float, dive and tread water is not a luxury, it’s a necessity. Beyond it being a means to survive (because natural disasters happen all the time), it is a time to heal.
_
Athletes faithfully utilize water to heal; cold plunges and hot tubs are made for revitalization. Humans are made of more than 60% water. We were designed to enjoy the waters.

If your children and/or parents haven’t created a loving bond with water, guide them. It’s our duty to continue sharing these sacred practices. Being immersed in water is more than a sport. If you haven’t created an intimate relationship with deep waters, I urge you to do so.

How to reset when you’re feeling burned out?
•
Since starting my yoga journey 9 years ago, I’ve developed a level of awareness that helps me to be more efficient with work and more intentional about rest. I understand my cycles of high productivity along with restorative periods. Was I paying attention to this before I started yoga? Nah, not really. I was always on “go” and multitasking.
•
Corporate America dictating your work and break schedule really dampens your natural cycle. We are taught to work 8 hours with (2) 15-minute breaks and (1) 30-60 lunch break for 5 days of the week every month with +/- 3 weeks of vacation hours.
•
My natural cycle doesn’t align with this so I knew I had to get creative with who I work with to allow the flexibility in schedule. Typically, I operate extremely well with a 90/30 work-to-rest schedule.
•

These are just a few mistakes that I have made when teaching yoga that I want to share so that you can avoid them.
•
#1: Yoga playlists that are available to the public must be rehearsed beforehand. I’ve made the mistake of choosing a relaxing playlist and halfway through the playlist, the tempo started to pick up and lyrics were recited in a different language. The problem is that if you don’t know what’s being said, then, how do you know what impact it will have on someone?
_
#2: Confirming pregnancies or injuries before class is crucial. The last thing you want to do is cue a pose that lands a student in pain. Yoga is a physical practice. You can get hurt. Breathing techniques can cause dizziness and lower carbon dioxide levels. You want to be aware of which students may require a little more attention during class.
_
#3. I’ve made the mistake of staying at the front of the class in my early teaching days. The problem is, if you never get off your own mat, then you’re not really teaching, you’re in your own practice. A solid yoga teacher should be able to lead from anywhere in the room.
_

✨ It helps strengthen your nervous system and reduce stress.

✨ It increases your endurance for physical activity.
✨ It boosts your immune system to help prevent disease.

Inhale to expand the belly, exhale in short, rhythmic pulses. Try 1-3 minutes to begin. Set the timer. Challenge yourself. Imagine you’re running a marathon; don’t rush it.

So the Kleshas are outlined in various philosophical texts, including the Yoga Sutras of Patanjali. Is this is a new concept to you, lemme break it down for you!
_
There are five primary Kleshas:

1. #Avidya (#Ignorance): This is the fundamental cause of all other Kleshas. It refers to a lack of true knowledge or understanding about the nature of reality, leading to confusion and misperception.

2. #Asmita (#Egoism): Asmita is the identification with the ego or the sense of “I” and “mine.” It involves a strong attachment to one’s self-identity and a tendency to define yourself in relation to your possessions, achievements and social roles.

3. #Raga (#Attachment): This Klesha involves desire and attachment to pleasurable experiences. It is the craving for sensory and emotional satisfaction, and it can lead to suffering when those desires are not fulfilled.

4. #Dvesha (#Aversion): Dvesha is the opposite of Raga. It involves aversion, hatred, or avoidance of unpleasant experiences. Like attachment, aversion can lead to suffering when we resist or reject aspects of our reality.

5. #Abhinivesha (Fear of Death): This Klesha is involves a intense fear of death or not wanting to exist anymore. It can manifest as a clinging to life and a resistance to change.

In Yogic philosophy, the practice of self-awareness, mindfulness and meditation is seen as a means to overcome the Kleshas. By understanding and transcending these mental and emotional obstacles, individuals can achieve inner peace, clarity, and liberation.

Traveling is a luxury that many people don’t get to experience often enough.

As a child, I was blessed to have visited many countries. #SaintVincentandTheGrenadines (pictured) is one of the places that I cherish the most.

As a #CaribbeanAmerican girl, I used to struggle with my identity because my Caribbean family would jokingly call me American like it was an insult. I grew up listening and dancing to #soca and #reggae music. We ate curry goat and jerk chicken every week. My elders influenced my etiquette, clothing, speech and spiritual practices. My people were bred and fed from soils of the Caribbean but that wasn’t enough to be able to claim my roots. The “Caribbean-American” term wasn’t a thing when I was younger.

Americans often ask if I’m Caribbean though. Apparently my cheekbones tell stories. In NYC, there’s a heavy presence of #Caribbean natives. They migrated there to create a better life.

I was born in Arkansas, where many other elders were bred and fed. I grew up eating Southern soul food and adopting the Southern hospitality.

As a military kid, my neighborhoods and schools were typically very diverse and protected which allowed us to cohabitate and evolve. Every city that we moved to or visited brought an entirely different culture into the mix.

I feel grateful to have experienced Asian and European cities as a child. I am able to recall pleasant childhood memories. I cherish them deeply.

I told myself that procreation will happen after I’ve attracted the life partners that will allow me to gift our children this kinda travel lifestyle. It’s a nonnegotiable for me. I know myself well enough to know that my children will be wanderers like me. They must be able to see many terrains and dig their little toes into black sand beaches.

I wish more people would prioritize travel. Some people overthink or neglect it because no one taught them how to travel. There’s a science to it; from budgeting to securing transportation and rooms to packing/unpacking.

Please prioritize family trips, #baecation, #solotravel even if it’s a quick train ride over a weekend.

Life is to be experienced. You deserve the world. 🌎

1. Your practice is more than what you do on the mat.
2. Demonstrating poses during class is ok. Practicing the poses throughout class is not.
3. Your students will neglect their breath often. Remind them of it.
4. It’s better to write and read meditation scripts than to have empty silence.
5. Yoga is best practiced in community so find your tribe and stay connected.
